transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for having me. I'm ready to answer your questions. Please go ahead.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Sure! My name is Emma, and I'm 20 years old. I live in a small town in Alabama, and I'm currently a college student, although I don't have a degree yet. I come from a low-income household, which makes things a bit tough for me financially. I rely on the local free clinic for my healthcare because I don’t have insurance. Right now, I’m dealing with a lot, especially because I recently found out I'm pregnant, and that’s been really overwhelming for me. I don’t have much support from my family, and I’m not sure what to do about the pregnancy. I also have some health issues, like gingivitis and not feeling well lately. Overall, I guess you could say I’m just trying to figure things out.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: I found out I was pregnant about three months ago. It was quite a shock for me because I wasn’t expecting it at all. I missed my period and took a home test, which confirmed it. I remember feeling a mix of emotions—fear, confusion, and even a little excitement, but mostly uncertainty about what to do next. Since I’m in college and don’t have a stable job or income, it’s been really stressful trying to figure out how I can handle this situation. Have you had any prenatal care yet?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: I actually started seeking prenatal care pretty shortly after I found out I was pregnant. I went to the local free clinic because that’s where I usually go for my health needs. The staff there were really kind, but I felt kind of out of place. Since I don’t have insurance, I was worried about how much everything would cost. They did some basic checks, like confirming the pregnancy and checking my overall health. It felt a bit rushed, though. I could tell they were busy, and I didn’t get to ask all the questions I had. They told me to come back for follow-ups, but I’m nervous about keeping up with that since my situation is so unstable right now. How do you feel about the care you're receiving? Do you feel it's adequate for your needs?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: I'm receiving my prenatal care at the local free clinic, and the staff there are generally friendly and supportive. I usually see a nurse practitioner who seems to know her stuff, but I haven’t had a chance to build a strong relationship with her yet. Our appointments are often pretty short because they have so many patients to see. I appreciate their help, but I sometimes feel like I’m just another number. I wish I could talk more about my concerns and get more personalized advice, especially about the pregnancy and my health overall. It can be a bit overwhelming, and I don’t always feel like I can express everything I’m going through. Do you think you’ll be able to continue seeing them for your care?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: I usually have prenatal appointments about once a month, but sometimes it feels like it’s more rushed than I would like. When I go in, I check in at the front desk, and then I wait for my name to be called. Once I’m in the exam room, the nurse usually takes my vitals and asks me a few questions about how I’ve been feeling. Then the nurse practitioner comes in, and we go over any symptoms I might have or any concerns. They do some basic checks, like measuring my belly and listening for the baby’s heartbeat, which is always a relief to hear. Most of the time, the appointments last around 15-20 minutes, and then I’m out the door. I sometimes wish I had more time to ask questions or discuss my worries, especially since I’m feeling so uncertain about everything. I guess I’m just trying to make sure I’m doing everything right for myself and the baby. Have you been able to discuss your lifestyle and any changes you might need to make during this pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: So far, I haven't had any major complications during my pregnancy, but I do have some health concerns that worry me. I mentioned earlier that I have gingivitis, which my nurse practitioner said I should be careful about since it can affect my overall health and the pregnancy. I also get these sore throats sometimes, which I think might be from that acute viral pharyngitis I’ve been dealing with. It makes me nervous because I don’t want to risk anything for the baby. I know I need to make some changes to my lifestyle, like eating better and cutting back on smoking and drinking, but it’s hard to stay motivated and figure out what’s best when I’m feeling overwhelmed. Have you had any discussions about your diet or lifestyle changes with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: Right now, I’m not taking any medications or supplements specifically for my pregnancy. I’ve been advised to take prenatal vitamins, but I haven’t started them yet because I’m not sure where to get them without spending too much money. I also don’t have a regular prescription for anything else, since most of my health issues are being managed at the free clinic. I know I should probably be taking better care of myself and looking into vitamins, but it feels overwhelming, especially with everything else I’m dealing with. Have you had any guidance on what supplements or medications are safe for you during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: My diet hasn’t been the best, to be honest. I tend to eat a lot of convenience foods because they’re cheaper and easier to make. I often skip meals or grab snacks that aren't very nutritious. I know I should be focusing on fruits, vegetables, and healthy proteins, but it’s hard when I’m busy with school and don’t have a lot of money. Sometimes I just grab fast food or processed meals because they’re more accessible. I’ve heard that nutrition is really important during pregnancy, but I feel lost on how to make better choices. I haven’t had a chance to discuss my diet in detail with my nurse practitioner, but I know I need to. Have you been able to access any resources or support for improving your nutrition?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: I'm feeling a mix of emotions, honestly. Some days are better than others. I often feel anxious about the future—about the baby, my education, and my financial situation. It's a lot to handle, and sometimes I feel really overwhelmed. I have moments where I feel excited about the possibility of being a mom, but then I think about how I don’t have much support and how I’m going to manage everything on my own. I get scared thinking about what it means to raise a child without a stable income or help from my family. There are also days when I just feel really sad and unsure about the whole situation. I wish I had someone to talk to who understands what I'm going through. Have you had any support systems in place, like friends or counseling, to help with your emotional well-being during this time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: I don’t really have a strong support network right now. My family isn’t really involved, and I feel a bit isolated. I have a few friends from college, but they’re also dealing with their own stuff, so I don’t want to burden them with my problems. Sometimes I talk to a friend who has a little more experience, but she’s busy with her own life. I think I could really use someone to talk to, maybe a counselor or a support group, but I haven’t looked into that yet. I just feel like I’m navigating this all on my own, which is really tough. It would be nice to have someone to lean on, especially during such a big life change. Have you looked into any resources or programs that might provide support for expectant mothers in your area?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: Honestly, I haven't put a lot of thought into a birth plan yet. It's all been so overwhelming with everything else going on in my life that I haven't really focused on the details of how I want the delivery to go. I guess I’m just trying to make sure I’m healthy and the baby is healthy first. I know I should probably start thinking about it, though. I’ve heard that having a plan can help ease some anxiety, but I’m not sure what my options are. I know I want to have a safe delivery, and I hope to be in a supportive environment, but the specifics are kind of a blur right now. Have you had any discussions with your healthcare provider about your options for delivery or any preferences you might want to express?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: I’ve mostly relied on the internet to learn about pregnancy and childbirth. I’ve looked up websites, forums, and even some videos to get information on what to expect. Social media has also been a big source, where I follow accounts that focus on pregnancy and parenting. Sometimes I feel like I get a lot of mixed messages, though, and it can be hard to know what information is reliable. I wish I could talk to someone face-to-face who could guide me through everything and answer my questions more thoroughly. I haven’t really found any books or resources that I feel comfortable with yet. Have you found any specific resources or recommendations that you think would be helpful for someone in my situation?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: Managing the financial aspects of my pregnancy has been really stressful. Since I come from a low-income background, I don’t have a lot of savings or support to fall back on. I rely on the free clinic for my healthcare, which helps with prenatal visits, but I’m still worried about costs associated with the baby, like diapers, clothes, and other essentials. I’ve been trying to save money wherever I can, but it’s tough with school expenses and my day-to-day needs. Sometimes I think about getting a part-time job, but I’m not sure how I would balance that with my studies and the pregnancy. I’ve thought about applying for assistance programs for expectant mothers, but I haven’t had the time or energy to look into it yet. I know I need to figure something out soon, though. Have you seen any programs or resources that could help with financial support for pregnant women?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: My pregnancy has definitely put a strain on my work situation, though I don't have a stable job right now. I used to have a part-time job, but I had to quit because I was feeling too overwhelmed with school and everything else going on. I’m worried about finding a job again, especially now that I’m pregnant. I think about how hard it would be to manage work, school, and taking care of a baby all at once. It makes me hesitant to look for something part-time because I don’t want to overcommit myself, but I know I need to think about how to provide for a baby. I’ve also thought about how some employers might not be understanding or supportive of my situation. Have you considered any job opportunities or resources that might support pregnant students in finding flexible work?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: I’ve thought a little about the postpartum period, but honestly, it feels a bit overwhelming to plan for right now. I know I’ll need to adjust to life with a newborn, and I worry about how I’ll manage everything on top of my studies. I’ve heard that the first few weeks can be really tough, and I’m concerned about how I’ll feel emotionally and physically after giving birth. I’d like to figure out some kind of support system for after the baby arrives, like maybe finding a local group for new moms or connecting with someone who can help. But I haven’t really done much planning yet because I’m just trying to focus on getting through the pregnancy first. It would be great to have a plan for things like childcare and how to balance my responsibilities, but right now, it feels like a lot. Have you been able to explore any resources or support systems for new mothers that could help during the postpartum period?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
